text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!IndigenousLanguagesOfTheAmericas]]%0a%0a!Kizh or Tongva of CA%0a%0a:Author: Spencer_L%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aWe will be discussing the language and the history of the Kizh/Tongva tribe in Southern California%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aChino Hills California is my hometown. I’ve been living here since 3rd grade, so I have an emotional attachment to this place. The traditional stewards of the land were the Gabrielino-Tongva Indian Tribe. The Gabrielino_Tongva Tribe also call themselves the San Gabriel band of Mission Indians. They were also referred to as Gabrieleno and Fernaneno by colonizers. Though Tongva is the most popular name, others choose to identify as Kizh, as they disagree with the name Tongva. To the best of my ability, the IPA transcription of Tongva is [tovaːŋaɹ].%0a%0aThe most reason treaty that relates to the land in question is the assimilation policy lead by President Eisenhower's administration. Though the successfulness of the policy is not quite clear, sources from websites curated by the Kizh still state that they are fighting for and rights and official recognition. As of today, the Gabrielino-Tongva Indian Tribe is officially recognized by the State of California. However, it is still not recognized by the Federal Government. %0a%0aThe language spoken by the Gabrielino-Tongva Indian Tribe is called Gabrielino. It is a Uto-Aztecan language that is closely related to Serrano, Hopi, and Shoshone. Due to heavy enslavement and violence towards the Native Americans in the past, language loss has been a major issue in California. The last noted fluent speaker of Gabrielino was in the early 21st century. Since the 1940's, Gabrielino has not been spoken since. Only recently, younger generations of Gabrielino-Tongva descent have been trying to revive the language. Due to this, there are currently many online sources that teaches the language. Due to observations from wide studies of the revitalization of the language from both descendants of the Gabrielino-Tongva Indian Tribe and major higher educational institutions, it seems to be that is is quite successful. Gabrielino was the everyday language before its downfall. Most people of Gabrielino descent right now speak English. Due to the fact that there are no recorded fluent speakers of Gabrielino, there is no guarantee that the original language can be revived to its fullest.%0a%0aI have listed sources that were used to research on the Gabrielino language. Most pages contained very little information of the history of the language. Most sites curated by descendants of the Gabrielino-Tongva Indian Tribe contained only vocabulary from the langauge. Wikipedia was able to offer some insight phonology and the morphology.%0a%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tongva_language%0ahttp://www.native-languages.org/gabrielino_words.htm%0ahttp://www.native-languages.org/gabrielino.htm%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uto-Aztecan_languages %0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210324-061717-257860#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Reclamation of the Gabrielino/Tongva language %0a-> - evelynC%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aAs Gabrielino came from Southern California, much of the reclamation efforts of Gabrielino stem from the greater Los Angeles area. One particular effort that has been spreading the Tongva language is a Facebook page that is currently run by Pamela Munro, a professor of linguistics at UCLA. On the Facebook page, different guides on relevant phrases in today's society are uploaded to spread more knowledge on the language. As there are very little speakers of the language today, the Facebook page provides a place for people all over to visit if they are intrigued or would like to learn more. Munro dislikes the use of the word "extinct" for Tongva as she believes its culture and history is still relevant to many people today.%0a%0aSources: https://newsroom.ucla.edu/stories/ucla-linguist-gabrieleno-tongva-indians-use-social-media-to-revive-extinct-language https://www.latimes.com/projects/la-me-col1-tongva-language-native-american-tribe/%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210324-061717-257860#%0a%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a#foxbegin 210412-221656-546230#%0a(:if1 equal {$:Author} {$Author}:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a(:if1end:)%0a#foxend 210412-221656-546230#%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: :)%0a(:Category: IndigenousLanguagesOfTheAmericas:)%0a#foxbegin 210508-011308-661230#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Wax Cylinder Recordings of Gabrielino-Tongva Tribe %0a-> - CharlieP%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI recently saw a project at UC Berkeley of digitizing old wax cylinder recordings of Native California tribes using photographic reconstruction. Most of the recordings were created as an attempt to capture the speech of some of the last native speakers of those California tribes, by the Bureau of American Ethology. It's a long shot away from reviving the language, and some of the recordings are a pretty bad quality, but I still think it's important to try to at least salvage these recordings while we still have them. Wax cylinders break down pretty quickly due to mold and natural decay, so digitizing them is definitely important. Here's a recording of a member of the Tongva tribe: %0a%0ahttps://portal.hearstmuseum.berkeley.edu/catalog/6408246b-8bb6-43bf-98f9-2c478c617e9b %0a%0aSources: %0ahttps://www.neh.gov/grants/preservation/documenting-endangered-languages%0ahttps://hyperallergic.com/397995/wax-cylinder-optical-scanning-uc-berkeley/%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210508-011308-661230#
