 people of Gabrielino descent right now speak English. Due to the fact that there are no recorded fluent speakers of Gabrielino, there is no guarantee that the original language can be revived to its fullest.%0a%3c %0a%3c I have listed sources that were used to research on the Gabrielino language. Most pages contained very little information of the history of the language. Most sites curated by descendants of the Gabrielino-Tongva Indian Tribe contained only vocabulary from the langauge. Wikipedia was able to offer some insight phonology and the morphology.%0a%3c %0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tongva_language%0a%3c http://www.native-languages.org/gabrielino_words.htm%0a%3c http://www.native-languages.org/gabrielino.htm%0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uto-Aztecan_languages %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a---%0a> Chino Hills California is my hometown. I’ve been living here since 3rd grade, so I have an emotional attachment to this place. The traditional stewards of the land were the Gabrielino-Tongva Indian Tribe. The Gabrielino_Tongva Tribe also call themselves the San Gabriel band of Mission Indians. They were also referred to as Gabrieleno and Fernaneno by colonizers. Though Tongva is the most popular name, others choose to identify as Kizh, as they disagree with the name Tongva. To the best of my ability, the IPA transcription of Tongva is [tovaːŋaɹ].%0a> %0a> The most reason treaty that relates to the land in question is the assimilation policy lead by President Eisenhower's administration. Though the successfulness of the policy is not quite clear, sources from websites curated by the Kizh still state that they are fighting for and rights and official recognition. As of today, the Gabrielino-Tongva Indian Tribe is officially recognized by the State of California. However, it is still not recognized by the Federal Government. %0a> %0a> The language spoken by the Gabrielino-Tongva Indian Tribe is called Gabrielino. It is a Uto-Aztecan language that is closely relat