diff:1616566637:1615572517:=57,67c57%0a%3c #foxbegin 210324-061717-257860#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Reclamation of the Gabrielino/Tongva language %0a%3c -> - evelynC%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c As Gabrielino came from Southern California, much of the reclamation efforts of Gabrielino stem from the greater Los Angeles area. One particular effort that has been spreading the Tongva language is a Facebook page that is currently run by Pamela Munro, a professor of linguistics at UCLA. On the Facebook page, different guides on relevant phrases in today's society are uploaded to spread more knowledge on the language. As there are very little speakers of the language today, the Facebook page provides a place for people all over to visit if they are intrigued or would like to learn more. Munro dislikes the use of the word "extinct" for Tongva as she believes its culture and history is still relevant to many people today.%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources: https://newsroom.ucla.edu/stories/ucla-linguist-gabrieleno-tongva-indians-use-social-media-to-revive-extinct-language https://www.latimes.com/projects/la-me-col1-tongva-language-native-american-tribe/%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210324-061717-257860#%0a---%0a> %0a
